Digital Differential Analyzer (DDA) Algorithm

The DDA algorithm is a simple and widely used method for rasterization of lines in computer graphics. It is a scan-conversion algorithm that generates points of a line at discrete intervals between the start and end points. The algorithm uses floating-point arithmetic to incrementally calculate intermediate points along the line based on its slope.

Algorithm Description

1. Input: Coordinates of the two endpoints of the line,  and .


2. Calculate differences:



\Delta x = x_1 - x_0, \quad \Delta y = y_1 - y_0

\text{steps} = \max(|\Delta x|, |\Delta y|)

4. Calculate increment values for each step:



X_{\text{inc}} = \frac{\Delta x}{\text{steps}}, \quad Y_{\text{inc}} = \frac{\Delta y}{\text{steps}}

x = x_0, \quad y = y_0

For each step, plot the pixel at 

Increment:


x = x + X_{\text{inc}}, \quad y = y + Y_{\text{inc}}

Characteristics

Produces smooth lines even for non-integer slopes.

Simple to implement but uses floating-point operations, which can be slower than integer-only algorithms like Bresenhamâ€™s line algorithm.

Works efficiently for lines with any slope.


Advantages

Easy to understand and implement.

Can be extended to draw curves and other shapes.


Disadvantages

Involves floating-point calculations.

Requires rounding operations at each step, which may introduce small computational errors
